<h2>Mathematical formulas</h2>
<h3>Linear Equations</h3>
<p>A linear equation is any equation that can be written in the form</p>
<h2><span class="formula">ax + b = 0</span></h2>
<p>where <span class="simvols">a</span> and <span class="simvols">b</span> are real numbers and <span class="simvols">x</span> is a variable. This form is sometimes called the standard form of a linear equation. Note that most linear equations will not start off in this form. Also, the variable may or may not be an <span class="simvols">x</span> so don‚Äôt get too locked into always seeing an <span class="simvols">x</span> there.</p>
<h3>Quadratic Equation</h3>
<p>The standard form of a quadratic equation looks like this:</p>
<h2><span class="formula">ax<sup>2</sup> + bx + c = 0 </span></h2>
<p>where <span class="simvols">a</span>, <span class="simvols">b</span>, <span class="simvols">c</span> are known values and <span class="simvols">x</span> is the variable or unknown (we don't know it yet). Also, <span class="simvols">a</span> can't be 0.</p>
<h3>The area of a circle (A)</h3>
<p><span class="simvols">œÄ</span> (Pi) times the radius (r) squared:</p>
<h2><span class="formula">A = œÄ √ó r^2</span></h2>
<p>or, when you know the diameter (D):</p>
<h2><span class="formula">A = œÄ / 4) √ó D^2 </span></h2>
<p>or, when you know the circumference (C):</p>
<h2><span class="formula">A = C^2 / 4 √ó œÄ </span></h2>
<h3>Intersection</h3>
<p>The intersection of two sets A and B, denoted by A ‚à© B, is the set of all objects that are members of both the sets A and B. In symbols,</p>
<h2><span class="formula">A ‚à© B = { x : x ‚àä A and x ‚àä B } </span></h2>
<p>That is, x is an element of the intersection A ‚à© B if and only if x is both an element of A and an element of B.</p>
   


  





   


